<br>
1) In general, people are self-interested.<br>
<br>
2) In general, people chafe under excessive restrictions. But at the same time, they complain about lawlessness and anarchy.<br>
<br>
3) In general, the strong will dominate the weak.<br>
<br>
4) In general, the weak don't usually band together to tell the strong to behave themselves.<br>
<br>
What I'm saying is...I don't think FFA will be here tomorrow, or next month....but the old-timers who &quot;settled&quot; Brell and worked out today's systems are disappearing. There is a new generation that feels like they've had the shaft (whether true or not) and are chafing under today's rules.<br>
<br>
I'm not in favor of FFA...I'm one of those folks who'd rather have a complicated reservation system and wait his turn rather than find the big, important mobs getting camped or guild wars starting over who has killed CT or Inny or Trak the last 10 times. If we go FFA, there will be guild wars. Maybe that isn't so bad since it would force many of the small guilds to unite, merge, or simply be more self-assertive. But, I have to think that anything that creates more rancor is a bad thing for a community.<br>
<br>
Guess I'm rambling. I'm just concerned that we're rolling towards FFA or that some of the &quot;up and coming&quot; guilds may decide not to play by the rules. For now, that can be controlled. But, can it be forever? Or how would we do that? Should we do that? Who gives us the right if we do? Just too many dangerous questions...<br>
<br>
Valgrave Greysoul<br>
Necromancer (58th level)<br>
<br>
